@danteleonbjj talks about the Importance of wrestling for No Gi Jiujitsu @grapplingindustries Ohio

#grapplingindustries #stuartcooperfilms #jiujitsu #bjj #nogi #wrestling #takedowns #grappling #pedigosubmissionfighting

Here I dismount to the side to try finish and my opponent with the arm triangle. 

There must have been some space so I decide to move back into mount and set it up again but my opponent times a nice bridge.

I was able to keep a dominant position and not get rolled off into guard by gripping onto his far tricep and locking my feet on the side of his hip and posting on my head.

I then transition to an arm lock but it just slipped out of my grip and I miss that submission too. 

I then decide to just go for the rear mount position by getting a grip of his far lat to pull myself in and line up my hips and eventually getting the body triangle. 

@grapplingindustries @adaptjiujitsu @stuartcooperjiujitsu @diazcombatsports 

#grapplingindustries #jiujitsu #bjj #nogi #grappling #scjj #stuartcooperjiujitsu #armtriangle #brazilianjiujitsu #jiujitsulifestyle #jiujitsulife #bjjlifestyle #stuartcooperfilms

Cloverleaf submission @grapplingindustries Denver

In this match I got a feel for my opponents strength and wrestling right away. After feeling a few of his powerful collar ties and snap downs I knew it would be very difficult to get on top of him and get upper body submissions. 

Instead, I timed one of his takedowns by sneaking my left leg to the inside position so that when we landed I could use the momentum to elevate his hips and bring him into the Cross Ashi position to finish with the cloverleaf.

I’m here at @cpistemcells in Tijuana to fix some serious disc issues in my neck, arthritis in my right elbow & torn meniscus’s in both my knees from years of training in “The Gentle Art”

Day One:

• MRI Scans
• Bloodwork
• Ozone IV 
• Myers Cocktail IV 
• NAD+ IV Drip
• PEMF Therapy on Neck, Elbow & both Knees

First thing this morning we got picked up by the shuttle bus at 8:00am at the Hyatt place in Tijuana. (Everything is well organised and made really easy for you)
We were then taken straight to the clinic to get MRI scans.
Once complete the shuttle picks you up and takes you straight to the hospital to start the first of many treatments. 

After your blood they first start with OZONE IV Therapy. 
It boosts circulation, promotes healing and relieves pain in wound and fractures. It also improves your circulatory system by cleaning arteries and veins. 

Next is the MYERS COCKTAIL. This helps with detoxification, energy production & Increases the blood concentration of essential vitamins and minerals. The Myers’ formula consists of high doses of B vitamins, vitamin C, and minerals (magnesium and calcium)

Then it’s PEMF Therapy. Pulsed Electro-Magnetic Field (PEMF) therapy uses technology to stimulate and exercise cells to help resolve cellular dysfunction and to support overall wellness. These energy waves work with your body’s natural magnetic field to improve healing.

And finally we finish with NAD+ IV which is something I already do every 2 weeks because of the amazing benefits I feel. 
NAD+ also known as nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide (NAD) is an intravenous treatment that helps stimulate cell regeneration in your body. NAD is a coenzyme derived from vitamin B3 that interacts with elements in your body to promote healing.
These include improved cognitive function, anti-aging, stress, depression and anxiety symptoms, boosts immune system and response to inflammation and enhances athletic performance. 
It also helps people with drug addictions, especially opiate addicts who are going through the PAWS phase. 

All these treatments help to potentiate the stem cells which i will be getting on Wednesday & Thursday. 

Tomorrow we continue….. #cpistemcells

Day Two @cpistemcells 

• 500mg NAD+
• PEMF Therapy (Round Two)
• X Ray
• EKG
• Apatone
• Dr appointment on MRI Results

We start the day with a high dose of NAD+ which takes about 3 hours to drip. You could do it quicker but it can make you feel very nauseous and dizzy. After it’s finished you feel extremely clear headed, energised with a huge boost in mood.

I then started round 2 of the PEMF therapy on both my knees, elbows and neck. This machine only stays on each joint for 3 mins. 

I was then taken for a quick X Ray on the lungs and an EKG was also taken. 

We were then given a pill of Apatone which is pharmaceutical grade vitamin C and Vitamin K3 combined.
Apatone is a very powerful medicine with many benefits and is also used as an alternative cancer treatment. 

I finished the day with a visit to the Dr to discuss the MRI results. Both the space in my knees has narrowed considerably to the point where they are almost bone on bone. A lot of the medial meniscus has worn away in both knees and they both have partial tears.
The Dr is planning to inject 20 million stem cells into each of my knees tomorrow. If I’m disciplined with the recovery I should be able to gain some space back in both of my knees and hopefully regenerate some meniscus tissue too. 

My right elbow shows pretty severe inflammation and arthritis after the elbow surgery I had last year to remove bone fragments. It never fully recovered and feels weak and painful almost all the time after any kind of exercise. 
Good news is the stem cells will be injected right into the elbow where it should help to regenerate the damaged tissue and reduce the inflammation and pain. 

Then finally my neck. The MRI showed degenerative disc disease and 4 bulging discs. There is a lot of degeneration in the facet joint and discs C5, C6 & C7. The space between each disc is also very narrow with little cushion. 
(This is from years of playing inverted guard in Jiujitsu)
So tomorrow they will inject stem cells right into 3 discs and the facet joints. This should help regenerate a lot of the tissue and give me the space back between the discs.

Day Three @cpistemcells

• Stem Cell Injections 
• Hyperbaric Chamber
• PEMF Therapy round 3 
• Apatone

On Wednesday at around 11am I got picked up by the shuttle and taken straight to the hospital for my stem cell injections. (I had to be fasted for 12 hours) 
Before the procedure they injected me with Tylenol for the pain and an antibiotic IV to prevent infection. 
I was heavily sedated throughout and didn’t feel a thing. After waking up from the procedure I felt quite good but as the meds wore off I started to feel the throbbing pain from the injections. But the pain does subside considerably after 24-36 hours and there is always a nurse and Dr close by to help you ease the pain with medications.

I had discs C5, C6, C7 and the facet joints injected in my neck and then my right elbow. 

For my knees CPI recommended the new Chondrocyte stem cell injections because a lot of the cartilage has eroded away to the point where I’m pretty much bone on bone. 

Autologous (from the patients body) Chondrocytes are FDA approved but require arthroscopic surgery for removal of cartilage and a 3-4 inch incision and surgery for placement. But CPI have been able to make it from the umbilical cord lining and engineer it to a chondrocyte which is a cartilage like cell that doesn’t require surgery for removal or placement.

These chondrocytes are recommended for injuries that need cartilage regrowth and they are combined with the Hypoxic Mesenchymal Stem Cells. The new scaffolding system holds the cells in place while promoting the perfect environment for the cells to grow. 
This should help regenerate the cartilage in my knees giving me that space and cushion back between the bones. 

After the stem cells I was taken straight to the Hyperbaric chamber for an hour. 
This Chamber (HBOT) reduces swelling while flooding the tissues with oxygen. The high pressure in the chamber increases the amount of oxygen in the blood. HBOT aims to break the cycle of swelling, oxygen starvation, and tissue death.

Eddie Bravo’s Take On Wrestling in ADCC,
Marcelo Garcia, Gordon Ryan & Jean Jacque
Machado.

Eddie Bravo is a Brazilian jiu-jitsu black belt under Jean Jacques Machado and founder of the Eddie Bravo Invitational (EBI). Bravo made his mark in competitive jiu-jitsu by submitting Royler Gracie at the ADCC Championship (2003), after which he launched his 10th Planet jiu-jitsu team, a program that became widely publicized, gathering a huge following in the grappling and mixed martial arts (MMA) communities.
Eddie’s views on grappling turned towards positions such as the rubber guard, the twister and a half guard move Bravo labeled as the lock down, these caught the eye of several MMA fighters who sought Bravo to learn his method. Fighters such as Alan Belcher, Tony Ferguson, Matt Horwich or Vinny Magalhaes, to name a few.
In 2003, after winning his weight division at the North American ADCC trials, Bravo was handed a chance to compete against the top competitors of the gi world, in a high-level no-gi event. Bravo had gained somewhat of an audience, by commentating for the broadcast of a popular MMA organization, where he expressed his views against the traditional style of Brazilian jiu-jitsu being utilized by most in the sport’s community. Bravo started the tournament well, beating Gustavo Dantas, a former brown belt world jiu-jitsu champion by way of RNC.

He faced Royler Gracie in the ¼ final of the
tournament, in the under 66kg/145lbs bracket. Royler was 38 years old at the time but still regarded as one of the favorites to win the division, being also one of the most accomplished members of the Gracie family in the sport. Bravo did exceptionally well against Royler, submitting him by way of triangle choke as the Gracie tried one of his trademarked knee sliding guard passes.

@sugasean & @timwelchmt we’re both @cpistemcells last year to fix up some injuries from years of training MMA and Jiujitsu. Sean had some tendinitis in his knee and Tim had a lot of issues with his shoulder to the point where he couldn’t train or sleep properly. 

Sean is now fighting for the UFC Bantamweight title tonight and Tim is back teaching & training 💯 pain free. 

I myself am on week 9 post stem cell procedure and I’m really starting to feel the results. Both my knees no longer have pain or stiffness as they were almost bone on bone. My neck feels 100 times better and I can finally move my head to both sides without any stiffness or nerve pain. I’m excited to see how I feel in another month when I return to some light training. 

If you have an injury that just won’t heal, I would really recommend contacting @scottyotm or @loladranker from CPI. 
I’m so glad I never went down the surgery route for my neck. Dr’s we’re recommending to possibly fuse the discs in my neck or have disc replacement surgery. 
Instead I chose to do stem cells first and I definitely made the right choice! Truly amazing regenerative healing technology! 🔥

@eddiebravo10p talks to @joerogan about using the world class regenerative stem cells from @cpistemcells to fix both of his shoulders.

I personally took a trip down to CPI in Tijuana, Mexico around 10 weeks ago to heal up a number of Injuries that resulted from 15 years of Jiujitsu.

I had heard amazing things about this new regenerative medicine and how it can be a much better solution than surgery to to heal sports injuries.
 
So I contacted my good friend @scottyotm for more info and next thing you know I'm in Mexico getting 120 million stem cells injected into 3 discs and 2 facet joints in my neck, both of my knees and my right elbow. 

Already in such a short amount of time I am feeling the incredible results.

Just a few months ago I was really starting to feel the wear and tear on my body from years of grappling and I am only 38 years old. I couldn't help but think what I would be feeling like at 48? It was a scary thought!

When I would wake up in the morning my body really felt like it was in it's 50's, but now it feels like i'm 25 again! 🙌

I have not trained Jiujitsu for 3 months now to let the Stem cells do their work. But I really feel that this is going to add years onto my Jiujitsu career and allow me to train pain free for many more years to come. 

I'll be posting my own video testimonial very soon talking about the injuries that I had and how the stem cells have helped heal them.

Big thanks to @edclayofficial @scottyotm 
@theopenrowkang @loladranker and all the staff at Cellular Performance Institute!🙏

To find out more about stem cell treatment message @cpistemcells on Instagram or visit their website.

Can’t thank this legend enough! @scottyotm is an OG in the martial arts community and one of the most generous people I’ve ever met. 

I first met Scotty in 2013 in Beijing, China at ADCC. A few months later he gave me a free place to stay in California while I was travelling around making jiujitsu films. He is always looking to help people the best way he can. 

They are doing amazing things down here @cpistemcells 

I first came here 6 months ago to get both my knees injected, my right elbow, then 3 discs and 2 facet joints in my neck. The results have been incredible so far and I’ll soon post a video detailing my injuries and recovery with the before and after MRI results.

This week I’m here in Tijuana for my follow up to see the progress of my recovery with another 30 million stem cells. 

My recovery has been so good that this time I decided to have my left elbow injected with 10 million stem cells and the remaining 20 million in an IV. 

Since my first visit I had a number of people DM me saying they were skeptical about stem cell therapy and there’s not enough science or data to prove that it works and it’s even placebo? 

Well let me tell you that this 💯 works and my recovery along with many other people I have met here has been truly amazing. 
I kept in contact with many people who had the procedures with me 6 months ago and they all had very positive results too. I couldn’t recommend this place enough especially for broken MMA & Jiujitsu athletes! 

Thankyou to everyone @cpistemcells for getting me back on the jiujitsu mats pain free! 🙏
